    <text>
        <body>
        	<div1 type="letter">
        		<pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0225"/>
        		<head>Jim to Mlle. Marcelle Guerin <date value="1916-01-18">Jan 18th 1916</date></head>
        		
        		<opener>
            <dateline><date value="1916-01-18">Jan 18th 1916</date></dateline>
            
            <salute>Dear Marcelle:</salute>
        		</opener>
        		
            <p>
            There isn’t
            any especial news.  One
            day is like the rest
            save for our little
            accidents.  To day a
            lieutenant in my present
            division smashed a
            machine, and as he did
            the same with another
            yesterday it holds us
            back for a day.  I
            have passed along rather
            fortunately so far and
            
            <pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0227" n="[p.2]"/>
            
            have passed more than 
            half of the section I
            found myself assigned
            to at first.  They
            had been waiting a
            month.  My delay in
            Paris was fortunate,
            and my arrival here
            well timed, as forty
            five new ones came 
            in just afterwards.
            The standard has
            been lowered a very 
            great deal.  This
            last outfit consists
            for the most part
            
            <pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0226" n="[p.3]"/>
            
            of rough necks.
            </p><p>
            I’ve been hoping
            to hear from you
            but have received no
            letter since my arrival
            eighteen days ago.
            </p><p>
            I hope that I will
            receive my brevet within
            six weeks but then
            that all depends on
            me, the weather, luck,
            and what machines
            are smashed.  You
            see we learn here
            on the most difficult, 
            the Bleriot, and do not
            
            <pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0228" n="[p.4]"/>
            
            get practice on double
            command machines.
            </p><p>
            We go into the air
            for the first &mdash; and all
            times &mdash; alone.  Its
            very amusing to watch
            the flights.  One expects
            to see some one come
            spilling down and
            break his neck any 
            moment.  No one has been
            killed since I arrived
            however.  The only trouble
            is we have no time.
            </p>
        		
        		<closer>
            <salute>Good night, dear,</salute>
            
            <signed>Jim.</signed>
        		</closer>
        		
            
